HEADWORD: Poignant
<hw>Poign"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., p. pr. of <ets>poindre</ets> to sting, fr. L. <ets>pungere</ets> to prick, sting. See <er>Pungent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pricking; piercing; sharp; pungent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>poignant</xex> spear.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Poynaunt</xex> sauce.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Pointed; keen; satirical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His wit . . . became more lively and <qex>poignant</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poignantly</ent>⟦br⟧
